          "en": "Open the window so the room is bright."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Atyu ya king arap ning bintana.",
          "en": "He is by the window."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "From Spanish 'ventana'. Refers to a window. Confidence: very high."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-puso",
      "word": "puso",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "heart"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "puso",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Dakal a lugud king puso ku para keka.",
          "en": "There is much love in my heart for you."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Tibuk ya ing puso ku.",
          "en": "My heart is beating."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Shared Austronesian root across Philippine languages. Can refer to the physical heart or to love/emotion figuratively. Spelling variant 'pusu' is also attested. Confidence: very high; attested in existing pack sentences."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-bisita",
      "word": "Bisita",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "guest",
        "visitor",
        "visit"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "bisita",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Atin bisita kami ngeni.",
          "en": "We have a visitor today."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Mayap ya ing bisita da king bale mi.",
          "en": "Their guest at our house is kind."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "From Spanish 'visita'. Widely used in Kapampangan and Tagalog alike. Can function as a noun (guest/visitor) or refer to the act of visiting. The verb form is 'mamisita' (to visit/pay a visit)."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-kasal",
      "word": "Kasal",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "wedding",
        "marriage ceremony"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "kasal",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Masaya ya ing kasal da.",
          "en": "Their wedding is joyful."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Munta kami king kasal na ning anak da.",
          "en": "We are going to their child's wedding."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "From Spanish 'casar' (to marry). Used across Philippine languages including Kapampangan. Refers to the wedding ceremony or the institution of marriage. The verb form is 'magkasal' (to get married)."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-libru",
      "word": "libru",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "book"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "libro",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Atin ku libru ning Kapampangan.",
          "en": "I have a Kapampangan book."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Mamasa ya ning libru.",
          "en": "He/she is reading a book."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Kapampangan vowel-shift form of Spanish loanword 'libro'. The shift from final -o to -u is characteristic of Kapampangan phonology; compare 'trabahu' (trabaho), 'libru' (libro)."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-opisina",
      "word": "opisina",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "office"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "opisina",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Munta ya king opisina.",
          "en": "He/she goes to the office."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Atyu ya king opisina na.",
          "en": "He/she is already at the office."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Spanish loanword from 'oficina', used identically in Tagalog and Kapampangan. Common in modern urban vocabulary."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-pelikula",
      "word": "pelikula",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "movie",
        "film"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "pelikula",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Mayap ya ing pelikula.",
          "en": "The movie is good."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Munta kami lawen ing pelikula.",
          "en": "We are going to watch a movie."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Spanish loanword from 'pelicula'. Used identically across Philippine languages for movie or film."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-pila",
      "word": "pila",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "line",
        "queue"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "pila",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Atin a pila ngeni.",
          "en": "There is a line now."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Munta ka king pila.",
          "en": "Get in line."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "From Spanish 'fila' (row/line). The primary modern meaning is a queue or line of people. Also can mean a saw (tool) in some contexts, but queue is the everyday usage."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-kwentu",
      "word": "kwentu",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": [
        "story",
        "tale",
        "account"
      ],
      "relatedTagalog": "kwento",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Mayap ya ing kwentu na.",
          "en": "His/her story is good."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Sabian me ing kwentu mu.",
          "en": "Tell me your story."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Spanish loanword from 'cuento' (story/tale). Kapampangan form 'kwentu' vs. Tagalog 'kwento' — reflecting the Kapampangan final-vowel shift."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-bag",
      "word": "bag",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": ["bag", "purse", "handbag"],
      "relatedTagalog": "bag / bag",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Atin ku bag ku king trabahu.",
          "en": "I have my bag at work."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Maragul ya ing bag na.",
          "en": "Her bag is big."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "English loanword widely used in Kapampangan and Filipino languages. Refers to a bag, purse, or handbag. The English form 'bag' is the standard usage, reflecting the heavy English influence on modern Kapampangan vocabulary."
    },
    {
      "id": "ev-biyaya",
      "word": "biyaya",
      "partOfSpeech": "noun",
      "translations": ["grace", "blessing", "gift", "favor"],
      "relatedTagalog": "biyaya",
      "examples": [
        {
          "kp": "Dakal a biyaya para keka.",
          "en": "Many blessings for you."
        },
        {
          "kp": "Salamat king biyaya mu.",
          "en": "Thank you for your blessing."
        }
      ],
      "notes": "Shared Philippine word ultimately from Sanskrit 'viyaya' or related root, conveying grace, blessing, or divine gift. Used in religious and everyday contexts. Both Kapampangan and Tagalog use 'biyaya' for God's blessing or a benefactor's grace."
    }
